segments.text: I was starting to ask, what are the, what contributes to Aggie spirit?
This feeling of warmth and affection and respect that so many people, students, faculty, staff, and others have in school.
What is it that builds that?
I think that in my own instance,
I think it was the core of cadets.
I remember that it became apparent to me that, and I was also brought to my attention several times, that you are not important as C Company infantry.
The important thing is
see infantry, what it is like, what it does.
And you have an obligation to know every man in the company, which as a freshman I proceeded to memorize the names of every person and their hometown.
If you didn't
If you couldn't give the hometown, you might have it spelled out in a very emphatic manner.
Also, you know, I worried about this at first, Haskell, because it seemed like you were criticized everything you did.
And I was getting very discouraged.
And then I was surprised to find out by watching that this sophomore said that to everyone.
So then I began to get the feel of this thing.
It was a learning to live together and to make your contribution.
Now, also, you did not have to like someone.
You simply needed to know how to work with someone and to be courteous, even though you didn't like the language of the person.
Well, all right, but you accept the man as being a part of your unit.
We did things together.
And I noticed that today, out on the campus, they have tremendous organization that you can belong to.
But it is, and also, Haskell, we took care of each other.
I noticed this when I was director of the counseling center.
If you have someone in your dormitory that obviously is sick, you see that they get to the hospital.
All right, now I was going to say, you were saying that for you it was the core.
But later, in the 50s, 60s, 70s, you as a professional must have seen this transcend the core because there were so many who were not in it.
And so that had to be greater.
I had a grandson who came here in 1988.
It was a history maybe.
Tim.
Tim lived in Puryear Hall.
Now Puryear Hall was not what I used to call non-reg.
But they had their own organization.
They had certain leaders
that were designated.
And they did things together.
One of the things that also contributes to this over the years has been the intramural program.
We have for many years, to my knowledge, had the most extensive intramural program in the United States.
Well, that puts young men, they run together, they play together,
And this builds up a unity.
And it has tradition.
Now some profs come down here from east or west or somewhere, and that's the first thing they want to eliminate, are the traditions.
Well, my experience has been that if you have that faculty member stay five, six, seven years, he begins to change.
So Haskell, whatever it is, eats on the professor just as it does on the student.
I think it's a wonderful thing.
In this inclusiveness,
How much did it matter about the students' family wealth, ancestry, national background, et cetera?
Oh, that's an interesting point.
I don't think it makes any.
I sensed this the first week I was here.
It's remarkable.
And it was even so that I had some friends who were very well-off.
But you would never know it, because we all did things together.
No one tried to show off with this, that, or the other.
I think that if some way they could devise a method to allow a student to retain his heritage, retain his characteristics,
but learn to live with others and go ahead with your, well, your interests.
I was flabbergasted here a few weeks ago to see over television.
This is at the University of Virginia.
I was only on the campus of the University of Virginia for two days.
and I was deeply impressed with their honor system.
This was related to the black students and this fellow who was interviewing them was thrown completely off balance because they said we want what our rights are as it relates to
the functioning of living, getting instruction, but we want to be with our own.
And they had their own tables at the dining hall.
They said, we feel more comfortable this way.
And they in effect were saying, I'm not eating to win friends and influence people.
I'm eating because I'm with people that I am like.
We can live together.
We can work together.
The military does this.
I mean, when you get into the Navy or whatever it is, you have strong differences, but there are times when it's time to put it all together.
To me, one of A&N's many strengths is that
okay, so you grew up in the country and I didn't, so what?
Or, so you happen to be Germanic in ancestry and I happen to be Dutch, so what?
Let's see if we can work this math problem together, or let's see if we can share whatever else.
And it was this inclusiveness, which...
that if you're an Aggie, that's all that matters, if you're one of us.
And if you're not, then the old thing of highway six runs both ways was the answer.
If you don't like it, well, keep going.
All right.
Or within the Corps or without of the Corps, are there certain events where people share the experience
that you think helped to pull Aggies together?
Well, I feel that one thing, it's interesting.
We have all the differences in the world, but when we get out on Kyle Field and we're playing football, for example, the people
They are together.
Even the alumni.
There's a commonality.
And it's remarkable.
People are flabbergasted at how many people attend Ireland.
What about, have you got a time commitment?
No, no, but Melba wants us to take a break.
Let's jump to 1970.
Mr. Rutter dies early that year.
Jack Williams comes November the 1st.
Do you remember your first impressions of him?
Well, yes, I do.
But I think I may have commented on this.
My first meeting with President Wheeler was the, he asked that we come down to his office, Jack Dobson, director of the A&M adjunct.
Myself, who was the administrative person that, well, would answer to you or to a proper person as to how the program was doing and all that sort of thing.
And then we took Dean Maxwell with us because the courses tended to be in his college.
And Maxwell didn't have much to say until we were walking and got about halfway down to the system building and he said,
President Williams, but he said, I don't know why you're doing it.
He said the A&M adjunct has been given to Texas Tech and they're going to take over the first of June.
Well, we had about almost filled for the first six weeks and a great
number for the second six weeks.
And it was a very awkward situation.
Well, we got to President Williams' office and he commented that he was interested in the program.
And we faced this issue then, what are we going to do?
We have all these people who have sent their money in.
And President Williams called in Bob Cherry, the secretary, to the board.
And Bob explained that that had been worked out by tech.
And that was what they had said they wanted to do.
But they also though recognized the dilemma and they had a telephone meeting of the board and changed the closing date to the 1st of September.
President Williams was, he asked a lot of questions.
He was very much at ease, very interested in the program.
And I felt that we had a very competent man here.
I was the university's representative to the college board.
Bob Logan was the second one because of his scholarships and loans.
We tried to keep President Williams informed, and I think we did.
But I had this experience with President Williams.
He wrote me and said, I want you to write me a letter explaining how you feel about the scholarship program
where it is restricted completely with financial need and is that the best way for us to go?
Well, of course, under Bob Logan's leadership, the president's scholars were chosen basically on potential and what they demonstrated they had done.
And I backed this.
I think that there are other ways they could have designated those loans to people who were in need.
But I hesitated at the word scholarship.
But I got this letter from President Williams who said, please write me this.
So I wrote back and said, Mr. Bob Logan, who
heads up this work in the scholarships and loans, much better qualified than I.
And I did not want to presume on Bob Logan's field.
Well, I sent the letter.
Well, in about three days, I got this letter back.
And he said, I'm well acquainted with Mr. Bob Logan and his work.
But he said, that is not what I asked you.
I asked you to tell me what you thought.
And he said, I persist that you write me this letter.
Well, I did.
I did.
And I frankly think that President Williams had somewhat the same feelings.
I know Wayne Hall backed me on this.
Well, President Williams, later, he was on the board of the college entrance examination board.
And I felt a little awkwardness about the president of the university
Well, Haskell, I didn't know how to handle it.
It's kind of like a sergeant visiting with a major.
But, you know, I think he knew that.
And he's a great tease, you know.
But I saw him later, after he left.
I think he went to Houston.
Mm-hmm.
And he had come for some reason to a College Board meeting in San Antonio and he grabbed me and he was a very warm person.
But I would imagine that if you lollygagged around or you pulled some stupid stunt, it would be an entirely different relationship.
Soon after he got here, Horace Byers retired and John Calhoun became the new chief academic officer.
Describe any interaction you had with him and any evaluation you had with him.
Well, you know, with Dr. Byers?
No, well, Byers and then Calhoun.
Well, there was an interesting thing that happened about that.
Dr. Byers admitted to me, he said, I may have made an error in judgment there, and I should have had your center as one of the places that Dr. Calhoun would be taken and given an orientation.
And he said, I'm sorry, but I didn't make any mention.
Well, my feeling was that Dr. Calhoun really didn't know
may not have known that this organization was under him.
And I want to tell you that one of the most pleasant interviews I've had was the day you came by.
And you told me, I knew you, but you told me what your relationship was and
some things about could you do this and could you do that.
And for the first time, I felt that I had an academic person who understood what we were trying to do in the field of dialogue.
And Haskell, that was a warm feeling.
Now in those years,
in the Williams-Calhoun years, the counseling, was it counseling and testing?
What was the center called?
It was called the Academic Counseling Center.
Academic Counseling Center.
It reported to whom in those years?
To Dr. Barr.
But directly to him?
Yes.
Okay, all right.
And then under Calhoun, same way?
Yes, sir.
Okay.
Mm-hmm.
And the staff, by and large, included whom in that period of time?
In that period of time, there was myself and Dr. Hope.
But Dr. Hope, though, was later taken by Dean Huber as associate dean.
And Dr. Sarah Jones took over.
and was a very capable clinical psychologist.
Very, very capable.
Had Ulrich Kroll.
We had this young man, Ronald Lewis, who got his PhD, and he now has his own counseling center out away from the university.
He's done quite well.
We had a small staff, to be honest with you.
I sometimes wonder how in the world we got to work that.
Share with this record, what was a typical day's effort like?
What did day in and day out, what did the center do?
One of the things that I tried to do was to gear our work in such a way that there would be periods when we would emphasize certain things.
Like in the summer months would be bringing in the small groups of students, processing them, and getting them out.
Now, of course, when we open school, then we could put our energy into a different activity.
And that would be, say, academic counseling.
As we got into the fall, then there would be the problems of...
Well, we did a lot of vocational counseling.
And it was a good contribution.
People like Dr. Howard Gravitt.
Dr. Gravitt kept a very close eye on his pre-meds and pre-dental students.
If in the sophomore year they were having difficulty, then Dr. Gravitt would
arrange for the student to come over to us.
And we would try to answer what are the causing, what's causing these things.
We, in many instances, we were able to divert the student into choosing a field related to the medical field, but not the doctor of medicine.
Bob Cochran, Dr. Cochran was
a person who kept a close eye on his nuclear engineering student.
If it appeared in the sophomore year that they were not handling the background work, then Dr. Cochran would call me and send the student over.
Well, when these things happened, we simply tried to help the student look at the options.
and to have them choose.
As far as Dr. Gravitt or Dr. Cochran was concerned, we tried to write them a letter which would answer these questions, but would not break the confidence thing.
We also, we served in institutional research
Actually, when that concept first came out, no one in the college wanted it.
And they'd send the material to the counseling center.
And Lannis Hope did a lot of work on that.
We tried to keep our college's, our university's image
with those college universities over the country that were doing institutional research.
We did some institutional research.
We did, we couldn't do a whole lot, but we did enough that it was, correlation studies would be helpful in planning what is to be done.
Also, Dr. Wayne Hall called me over and said, Austin, we are not getting a good measure of the quality of our product.
And I want you to come up with something that will make it possible for us to make some judgments.
So I thought about it, I read, I looked around, and I found that the graduate record examinations had an advanced test, and that you could rent old copies of that.
So we tried this out, we gave the students
the test.
And we were really surprised at the relationship between the test and the program that they were going through.
So I suggested to Dr. Hall that we add the GRE aptitude test and the appropriate
advanced tests to the testing program of graduating seniors.
Dr. Hall said, well, we'll have to handle that carefully.
And what we did was we told the seniors
that this is a requirement for graduation.
Texas A&M University will pay for it.
It will not cost you anything.
You may have the scores for your own personal use.
And we pointed out that in some instances, the GRE test could be used in lieu of the civil service examination.
We had resistance.
Students like to resist.
But we were all capable people.
And we handled that all right.
Did you find a correlation between the grades they had earned, their general grade average, and the GRE?
Yes.
We found some stimulating things.
By the way, there was a, I think that Bill Carter, one of our graduate students, wrote his dissertation on this.
What we found was that, first, we were a much stronger university in terms of our product than we had imagined.
We're using a thousand as the base for graduate study.
Half of the graduating class of Texas A&M University would be eligible for graduate study to first class places.
Then we took the advanced test and we got normative data on those tests from the GRE people.
And for instance, in biology, the mean score for our students would put them in the 84th percentile of the national.
Very good.
Very good.
Economics was the same way.
Engineering did well.
Now math, math did not.
So Wayne Hall says, we've got to find out why.
So he calls in from Baton Rouge, I believe, a fellow who was recognized in his field of math teaching.
And he stayed with us two days.
And he said, well,
Rennie, you're not in as bad a shape as it appears.
He said, first, you do not have a thorough undergraduate program of math for math majors.
You're spending all your time as subsidiary courses for other colleges.
He said also you must strengthen your math courses in the undergraduate program because the students must have material that will give them that background.
So the math department went to work.
I want to point out here is that in all of my work I tried to
place it in such a way that the faculty would use it.
I was not telling them what to do.
It was to give them information.
For instance, when we were considering these things, we had every department on the campus send three professors over.
And they sat in the room we set up for this.
And they studied the test thoroughly.
And they made the decision whether or not
